    "id": 3066,
    "question": "An author of a book received royalties from four different formats: paperback, hardcover, e-book, and audiobook, as well as from both domestic and international sales. The author got 6% of the total domestic sales of the paperback version, 12% of the total domestic sales of the hardcover version, 8% of the total domestic sales of the e-book version, and 10% of the total domestic sales of the audiobook version. However, for international sales, the author received 1% less for each format due to additional expenses. \n\nIf 32,000 copies of the paperback version were sold domestically at $0.20 each and 3,000 copies were sold internationally at €0.18 each, 15,000 copies of the hardcover version were sold domestically at $0.40 each and 2,000 copies were sold internationally for €0.35 each, 10,000 copies of the e-book version were sold domestically at $0.15 each and 4,000 copies were sold internationally at €0.13 each, and 5,000 copies of the audiobook version were sold domestically at $0.50 each and 1,000 copies were sold internationally at €0.45 each, how much did the author earn?\n\nAssume an average exchange rate of 1.15 USD for 1 EUR during the sales period, and a taxation of 15% on the author's royalty income.\n\n### Answer:",
