    "question": "James has $75 in his wallet, consisting of one $50 bill, one $20 bill, one $5 bill, and 4 quarters. He finds 3 bills in his pocket: one $20 bill, one $10 bill, and one €5 bill (in euros). Additionally, he has the following coins: one £2 coin (in British pounds), one ¥100 coin (in Japanese yen), two 1₣ coins (in Swiss francs), besides 2 quarters and 3 dimes.\n\nWhile exchanging currencies, James is charged a 0.8% fee for converting British pounds, a 1.5% fee for converting Japanese yen, and a 1% fee for converting Swiss francs. The exchange rates are as follows: 1€ = $1.20, £1 = $1.35, ¥1 = $0.009, and 1₣ = $1.08. \n\nJames buys a present for his friend, which costs $88. To pay for it, he uses all the coins and bills he has, but he still needs to pay with the least amount of converted foreign currencies. \n\nTaking into account the exchange fees, how much money does he have left in US dollars? Also, what is the total amount spent on present after taxes and the total amount he needs to pay in euros, British pounds, Japanese yen, and Swiss francs? The sales tax on the present is 8%.\n\n### Answer:",
