    "question": "My mother used 300 grams (g) more than 2/5 of the cooking oil in the house yesterday, and 200 grams (g) less than 1/2 of the remaining cooking oil today. If the remaining cooking oil is 800 grams (g), how many kilograms (kg) of cooking oil were there before mother used it yesterday?\n\n### Answer:",
    "options": [
      "Option A",
      "Option B",
      "Option C",
      "Option D"
    ],
    "correct": 0,
    "explanation": "Let's denote the original amount of cooking oil as X grams.\n\nYesterday, your mother used \\( \\frac{2}{5} \\) of X plus 300 grams. So the amount of oil left after yesterday's use is:\n\\[ X - \\left( \\frac{2}{5}X + 300 \\right) \\]\n\nToday, your mother used \\( \\frac{1}{2} \\) of the remaining oil minus 200 grams. So the amount of oil left after today's use is:\n\\[ \\left( X - \\left( \\frac{2}{5}X + 300 \\right) \\right) - \\left( \\frac{1}{2} \\left( X - \\left( \\frac{2}{5}X + 300 \\right) \\right) - 200 \\right) \\]\n\nWe know that after today's use, there are 800 grams of oil left. So we can set up the equation:\n\\[ \\left( X - \\left( \\frac{2}{5}X + 300 \\right) \\right) - \\left( \\frac{1}{2} \\left( X - \\left( \\frac{2}{5}X + 300 \\right) \\right) - 200 \\right) = 800 \\]\n\nLet's simplify the equation step by step:\n\n1. Distribute the \\( \\frac{1}{2} \\) inside the parentheses:\n\\[ X - \\left( \\frac{2}{5}X + 300 \\right) - \\frac{1}{2}X + \\frac{1}{2} \\left( \\frac{2}{5}X + 300 \\right) + 200 = 800 \\]\n\n2. Simplify the terms inside the parentheses:\n\\[ X - \\frac{2}{5}X - 300 - \\frac{1}{2}X + \\frac{1}{2} \\left( \\frac{2}{5}X \\right) + \\frac{1}{2} \\cdot 300 + 200 = 800 \\]\n\n3. Combine like terms:\n\\[ X - \\frac{2}{5}X - \\frac{1}{2}X + \\frac{1}{2} \\cdot \\frac{2}{5}X - 300 + 150 + 200 = 800 \\]\n\n4. Find a common denominator for the fractions (which is 10):\n\\[ X - \\frac{4}{10}X - \\frac{5}{10}X + \\frac{1}{2} \\cdot \\frac{2}{10}X - 300 + 150 + 200 = 800 \\]\n\n5. Simplify the fractions:\n\\[ X - \\frac{4}{10}X - \\frac{5}{10}X + \\frac{1}{5}X - 300 + 350 = 800 \\]\n\n6. Combine the X terms:\n\\[ X - \\frac{9}{10}X + \\frac{2}{10}X - 300 + 350 = 800 \\]\n\n7. Simplify the X terms:\n\\[ X - \\frac{7}{10}X = 800 - 350 + 300 \\]\n\n8. Combine the constants:\n\\[ X - \\frac{7}{10}X = 750 \\]\n\n9. Multiply both sides by 10 to get rid of the fraction:\n\\[ 10X - 7X = 7500 \\]\n\n10. Simplify the X terms:\n\\[ 3X = 7500 \\]\n\n11. Divide both sides by 3 to solve for X:\n\\[ X = \\frac{7500}{3} \\]\n\\[ X = 2500 \\]\n\nSo the original amount of cooking oil was 2500 grams. To convert this to kilograms, we divide by 1000 (since there are 1000 grams in a kilogram):\n\n\\[ 2500 \\text{ grams} = \\frac{2500}{1000} \\text{ kilograms} \\]\n\\[ 2500 \\text{ grams} = 2.5 \\text{ kilograms} \\]\n\nTherefore, there were 2.5 kilograms of cooking oil before your mother used it yesterday.",
